04005nam a22004935i 9780226238920DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20152015ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014035709  a97802262389207 a10.7208/97802262389202doi  a(DE-B1597)550017  a(OCoLC)904339082  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aQC406b.B35 2015 7aSCI0000002bisacsh  aCC 6020qBVB2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/17651:1 aBall, Philip, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aInvisible :bThe Dangerous Allure of the Unseen /cPhilip Ball. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b70 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- t1 Why We Disappear -- t2 Occult Forces -- t3 Fear of Obscurity -- t4 Rays that Bridge Worlds -- t5 Worlds Without End -- t6 All in the Mind -- t7 The People Who Can’t Be Seen -- t8 Vanishing Point -- t9 Bedazzled and Confused -- t10 Unseen at Last? -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIf offered the chance—by cloak, spell, or superpower—to be invisible, who wouldn’t want to give it a try? We are drawn to the idea of stealthy voyeurism and the ability to conceal our own acts, but as desirable as it may seem, invisibility is also dangerous. It is not just an optical phenomenon, but a condition full of ethical questions. As esteemed science writer Philip Ball reveals in this book, the story of invisibility is not so much a matter of how it might be achieved but of why we want it and what we would do with it. In this lively look at a timeless idea, Ball provides the first comprehensive history of our fascination with the unseen. This sweeping narrative moves from medieval spell books to the latest nanotechnology, from fairy tales to telecommunications, from camouflage to ghosts to the dawn of nuclear physics and the discovery of dark energy. Along the way, Invisible tells little-known stories about medieval priests who blamed their misdeeds on spirits; the Cock Lane ghost, which intrigued both Samuel Johnson and Charles Dickens; the attempts by Victorian scientist William Crookes to detect forces using tiny windmills; novelist Edward Bulwer-Lytton’s belief that he was unseen when in his dressing gown; and military efforts to enlist magicians to hide tanks and ships during WWII. Bringing in such voices as Plato and Shakespeare, Ball provides not only a scientific history but a cultural one—showing how our simultaneous desire for and suspicion of the invisible has fueled invention and the imagination for centuries. In this unusual and clever book, Ball shows that our fantasies about being unseen—and seeing the unseen—reveal surprising truths about who we are.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aInvisibility. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226238920423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226238920.jpg  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles